{
  "concept_id": "newton_second_law_direction",
  "concept_name": "Newton's 2nd Law — Direction Matters (F = m·a as a Vector Equation)",
  "chapter": 8,
  "section": "8.4",
  "schema_version": "2.0.0",
  "class_level": 11,
  "source_book": "DC Pandey Class 11 Ch.8 Laws of Motion §8.4 (Newton's Second Law) — table-of-contents reference only; teaching authored from first principles. Phase 0 validation demo Sim 2 (session 56-plan, authored session 59). The atomic concept being taught is *direction*: F is a vector, a is a vector, m is a scalar, so a points where F points — NOT where v points. This is the most-confused concept in mechanics: stationary objects can have zero net force AND non-zero F (if balanced); velocity does not equal force; mass does not 'resist' a force, it scales the acceleration response.",
  "renderer_pair": {
    "panel_a": "parametric",
    "panel_b": "graph_interactive"
  },
  "available_renderer_scenarios": {
    "parametric": ["block_on_smooth_floor"]
  },
  "prerequisites": [
    "free_body_diagram",
    "vector_resolution"
  ],
  "real_world_anchor": {
    "primary": "A wheeled shopping trolley on a smooth, polished mall floor — friction is almost zero. You push it with a steady force from behind. The trolley does not move at a constant speed — it speeds up. The harder you push (more F), the faster it speeds up (more a). A loaded trolley (more m) speeds up slower for the same push. The trolley accelerates in the exact direction you push, even if it was already drifting sideways before you pushed. F = m·a is this rule, sharpened into a vector equation.",
    "secondary": "Hockey puck on a wet floor (Indian schools, polished tile during winter). Slide it across with a flick — that's an instantaneous push that gives it velocity. After the flick, no force, the puck drifts at constant speed. Now flick it sideways while it moves — the puck does NOT reverse, and it does NOT keep its original direction. It curves — because the new push gives it acceleration sideways, while velocity is still forward. Velocity follows from acceleration over time. They are not the same thing.",
    "tertiary": "Cricket ball on a smooth pitch hit at 30° upward by the bat. The bat applies force F at 30°. The ball accelerates at 30° (during contact). After contact, gravity takes over (a different F, pointing down). At every instant, a = F_net / m, and a points along F_net — the ball's velocity vector evolves from there."
  },
