            { "id": "s1", "text_en": "Trolley is already moving rightward at constant velocity. Now apply a force straight down." },
            { "id": "s2", "text_en": "Where does acceleration point?" },
            { "id": "s3", "text_en": "Down — along the force. Not along the velocity. Acceleration follows F, not v." },
            { "id": "s4", "text_en": "What does the trolley do? It curves. Horizontal velocity stays — no horizontal force, no horizontal acceleration. Vertical velocity grows from zero — because vertical acceleration acts on it." },
            { "id": "s5", "text_en": "This is exactly projectile motion. Gravity is a constant downward force. Horizontal velocity is unchanged. The path curves." }
          ]
        },
        "misconception_watch": [
          {
            "belief": "If F is downward, the trolley should go straight down",
            "visual_counter": "curved_path",
            "one_line_fix": "F sets a, not v. The trolley already had rightward v — that doesn't disappear. Instead, downward a builds up downward v on top of it. The result is curving, not straight."
          }
        ]
      },
